com.telek.telekmath.advanced.statistics.inferential

Class ChiSquareTests

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.telek.telekmath.advanced.statistics.inferential.ChiSquareTests

  • public class ChiSquareTests
extends java.lang.Object
    A class that has methods for Chi Square tests.
    Assumptions of Chi Square Tests:
    • All groups are disjoint.
    • All observed values are independent of each other.
    • All groups have an expected value higher than 5. (If not the groups will be merged into one)

    • Method Detail

      • fitsDistribution

        public static boolean fitsDistribution(double[] observedFreqs,
                                       double[] expectedFreqs,
                                       java.lang.String distType,
                                       double alpha)
        Performs a "goodness of fit" test. Which is the same as "test for independence" with one variable.
        This is the recommended method for you to use if you want to do this test without creating a frequency distribution table. All other methods that will do the same thing with a different type of array will create a casted double array (they will create a copy) and use this method with that copied array.
        Parameters:
        observedFreqs - observed frequencies array
        expectedFreqs - expected frequencies array, you will need to create this array on your own using the distribution that you're going to test
        distType - a string specifying the distribution type, must be one of these: "uniform", "normal", "poisson"
        alpha - a value in range [0,1] specifying the confidence level, if you want %99 confidence level then you need to enter 0.01 (%1) as alpha
        Returns:
        true if the frequency distribution fits the distribution specified with the distType parameter

        Performs a "goodness of fit" test. Which is the same as "test for independence" with one variable.

        alpha - a value in range [0,1] specifying the confidence level, if you want %99 confidence level then you need to enter 0.01 (%1) as alpha
